  DDEESSCCRRIIPPTTIIOONN

    The eellvviiss(1) utility is a text editor which emulates vvii(1) and eexx(1).

    The eellvviiss(1) utility can be installed under the names eexx(1) and vvii(1)
    (replacing the nnvvii(1) versions of eexx(1) and vvii(1)). You may also install
    eellvviiss(1) under the names vviieeww(1) and iinnppuutt. If eellvviiss(1) is installed on an
    NTFS partition, these extra names can be links to eellvviiss(1); see the ln(1)
    shell command.

    When invoked as vvii(1), the program behaves exactly as though it was
    invoked as "elvis". However, if you invoke eellvviiss(1) as vviieeww(1), then the
    readonly option is set as though you had given it the --RR flag. If you
    invoke the program as eexx(1), then eellvviiss(1) will start up in the colon
    command mode instead of the visual command mode, as though you had given
    it the --ee flag. If you invoke eellvviiss(1) as eeddiitt(1), then eellvviiss(1) will
    start up in input mode, as though the --ii flag was given.

    The eellvviiss(1) utility takes the following options:
    ++cmd
        The eellvviiss(1) utility executes the command cmd after loading the first
        file. A typical example would be "elvis +237 foo", which would cause
        eellvviiss(1) to start editing foo and then move directly to line 237. Cmd
        must be a colon command.
    --cc cmd
        The System V version of the ++ option. eellvviiss(1) executes cmd after
        loading the first file. A typical example would be "elvis -c 237 foo",
        which would cause eellvviiss(1) to start editing foo and then move directly
        to line 237. Cmd must be a colon command.

    --ee
        The eellvviiss(1) utility will start up in colon command mode (_ee_xx(1) mode).

    --ii
        The eellvviiss(1) utility will start up in input mode.
    --mm [file]
        The eellvviiss(1) utility will search through file for something that looks
        like an error message from a compiler. It will then begin editing the
        source file that caused the error, with the cursor sitting on the line
        where the error was detected. If you don't explicitly name a file,
        then "errlist" is assumed.

    --rr
        To the real vvii(1), this flag means that a previous edit should be
        recovered. The eellvviiss(1) utility, though, has a separate program,
        called elvrec(1), for recovering files. When you invoke eellvviiss(1) with
        --rr, eellvviiss(1) will tell you to run elvrec(1).

    --RR
        This sets the "readonly" option, so you won't accidentally overwrite a
        file.

    --ss
        This set the "safer" option, which disables many potentially harmful
        commands. It has not been rigorously proven to be absolutely secure,
        however.
    --tt tag
        This causes eellvviiss(1) to start editing at the given tag

    --vv
        The eellvviiss(1) utility will start up in visual command mode.
    --ww winsize
        Sets the "window" option's value to winsize.

